        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>9. Devonshire St | Portland Place</placeName>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Murray</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks for your note. It really makes no difference to me whether you give me a Bill, or a cheque at the time proposed, for the <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></formula> profits, i.e. <hi rend="superscript">£</hi>315,— Pray do whichever seems best to you. I have been vexed to find that some of my friends &amp; as I hear some booksellers, complain of the type of the new Edit. of the Origin.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I found no difficulty in reading the proofs, &amp; my eyesight now is not very good; yet the lines now do seem to me not very distinct.— But there is no help for it, so it is no use thinking about it.—</p>
<p>Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 a] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.2 now] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8239.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 9 March 1872</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The sixth edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> was cheaper than the earlier ones. It had a smaller typeface and less spacing between the lines.</note>
        </div>        
            
